title: Angleterre : Battu par West Ham, Arsenal laisse sa place de leader √† Liverpool
text:
Le milieu de terrain d‚ÄôArsenal Declan Rice tacle l‚Äôattaquant de West Ham Jarrod Bowen, le 28 d√©cembre 2023 en championnat d‚ÄôAngleterre √† Londres
Liverpool reste sur le tr√¥ne de la Premier League apr√®s la contre-performance de son d√©sormais dauphin, Arsenal, battu √† l‚ÄôEmirates Stadium par West Ham (2-0) jeudi en conclusion d‚Äôune 19e journ√©e qui aura vu perdre trois des cinq √©quipes de t√™te.
En plus des Gunners, Tottenham a √©t√© battu √† Brighton (4-2) alors que le troisi√®me Aston Villa avait c√©d√© en fin de match mardi √† Manchester United (3-2).
Cinq jours apr√®s avoir accroch√© les Reds √† Anfield Road (1-1), Arsenal a contre toute attente c√©d√© face √† l‚Äô√©quipe qui l‚Äôavait √©limin√©e de la Coupe de la Ligue d√©but novembre. Les Hammers ont donn√© raison √† l‚Äôanalyse de leur entra√Æneur David Moyes, qui assurait avant le match que cette ann√©e √©tait la meilleure de l‚Äôhistoire du club, avec notamment un triomphe en Ligue Europa Conf√©rence.
L‚Äôentra√Æneur d‚ÄôArsenal Mikel Artera se d√©sesp√®re pendant le match de championnat d‚ÄôAngleterre contre West Ham, le 28 d√©cembre 2023 √† Londres
Ils n‚Äôont pas conc√©d√© la moindre occasion dans la premi√®re demi-heure de jeu, et m√™me marqu√© peu avant le quart d‚Äôheure apr√®s une mauvaise appr√©ciation de Gabriel Magalhaes, qui a profit√© √† Tomas Soucek (0-1, 13e). L‚Äôancien d√©fenseur Lillois a √©galement perdu un duel a√©rien d√©cisif en seconde p√©riode face √† Konstantinos Mavropanos, suite √† un corner de Ward-Prowse (2-0, 55e).
Souvent efficaces face au but depuis le d√©but de la saison, les Gunners ont cette fois manqu√© de r√©alisme avec Saka (30e, 42e), Martinelli (37e), Gabriel Jesus (66e) puis Trossard dans le dernier quart d‚Äôheure. Le score aurait pu √™tre plus cruel si Benrahma avait transform√© son penalty dans le temps additionnel.
‚ÄúQuand on tire trente fois au but, qu‚Äôon a 2,6 expected goals et qu‚Äôon a autant de situations dans la surface de r√©paration, on n‚Äôimagine pas qu‚Äôil faille faire beaucoup plus pour marquer un but et pour gagner ce match‚Äù, a affirm√© Mikel Arteta en conf√©rence de presse.
Nomm√© il y a quatre ans, l‚Äôentra√Æneur des Gunners n‚Äôa pas comment√© le manque de profondeur de banc, alors que les entr√©es successives de Smith Rowe, Nelson et Nketiah n‚Äôont pas permis de faire la diff√©rence en seconde p√©riode.
Arsenal compte deux points de retard sur Liverpool, alors que West Ham, 6e, est √† l‚Äôaffut des places europ√©ennes, √† trois points de Tottenham et quatre points de Manchester City, vainqueur mardi √† Everton (3-1) et qui compte un match de plus √† disputer.
‚Äì Tottenham rechute lourdement ‚Äì
Peu avant, Tottenham avait s√©v√®rement rechut√© sur le terrain de Brighton (4-2) et rat√© l‚Äôoccasion de se rapprocher de la t√™te du championnat. Tottenham √©tait pourtant la meilleure √©quipe √† l‚Äôext√©rieur avant cette rencontre et finit la premi√®re moiti√© de saison sur une note n√©gative, malgr√© une bonne cinqui√®me place au classement, √† un point de Manchester City.
Meilleurs ces derni√®res semaines apr√®s un mois de novembre catastrophique sur le plan des r√©sultats, les Spurs ont montr√© un visage inhabituel avec beaucoup de passivit√©, comme sur cette action individuelle de Joao Pedro qui a pu passer en revue quatre joueurs et donner une balle en or √† Jack Hinshelwood, d√©marqu√© √† l‚Äôentr√©e de la surface de r√©paration (1-0, 11e).
Entre plusieurs occasions nettes pour Brighton (17e, 32e, 45e), le m√™me Joao Pedro allait ensuite transformer deux p√©nalties (23e, 75e), avec entre-temps un frappe puissante de Pervis Estupinan dans la lucarne oppos√©e de Vicario (63e). Alejo Veliz (81e) et Ben Davies (85e) ont r√©duit le score, trop tard pour faire douter les Seagulls.
Brighton se repositionne √† la huiti√®me place, √† six points de la premi√®re place europ√©enne.

author: Vidmate
title: Comment on Easy Baked Nachos Recipe by Vidmate
text:
When you‚Äôre looking for an easy dinner idea that you can make in less than 30 minutes and get tons of flavor, this easy baked nachos recipe needs to be on your go-to list!
(Recipe updated with new photos 3/19/2020.)
EASY BAKED NACHOS RECIPE
I often make this recipe with ground beef. If you look at the bottom of the post, I first created it for the site using ground beef. But my family loves chicken nachos too! When it comes to nacho dinner ideas, the easiest thing to do is change out the meat or cheese that you use!
So when I remade these sheet pan nachos, I happened to have chicken on hand. But you can use any meat that you want! They‚Äôd be great with steak too!
HOW DO YOU MAKE NACHOS NOT SOGGY?
My number one tip on avoiding soggy nachos has to do with the chips you use. Choose chips that are thicker. I love thinner tortilla chips that are more like the ones you get in a restaurant, but they‚Äôre not the best for making nachos.
My other tip for avoiding soggy nachos is to watch your layering. Making sheet pan nachos is the perfect way to get better nacho layering. With just a single layer of chips, it‚Äôs easier to layer everything while still covering every single chip!
HOW LONG DO NACHOS GO IN THE OVEN FOR?
You only need about 5 minutes to cook this nacho dinner recipe. You‚Äôre really just looking to melt the cheese.
HOW DO YOU MAKE PERFECT NACHOS?
Spreading the chips in a single layer is the key to making the perfect nachos! They‚Äôll stay crispy and every chip will have some delicious toppings on it!
WHAT CAN I ADD TO NACHOS?
Here are some ideas for topping your nachos:
- Cheddar Cheese
- Monterrey Jack cheese
- Colby Jack cheese
- Cheese Sauce
- Chicken
- Ground Beef
- Ground Turkey
- Ground Pork
- Shredded Chicken
- Shredded Pork
- Steak Strips
- Rice
- Black Beans
- Pinto Beans
- Refried Beans
- Charro Beans
- Onions/Green Onions
- Black Olives
- Corn
- Jalape√±os
Toppings to add after baking your nachos:
- Tomatoes
- Lettuce
- Avocado
- Salsa
- Guacamole
- Sour Cream
- Cilantro
EASY BAKED NACHOS RECIPE INGREDIENTS
To make oven-baked nachos, you‚Äôll need meat (I used chicken when I updated this recipe and ground beef in the original), beans (if desired), rice (if desired), taco seasoning, water, shredded cheese, tortilla chips, and any other toppings that you like to put on your nachos.
HOW TO MAKE SHEET PAN NACHOS
Before you get started on the food, heat the oven to 425¬∞F.
Brown your meat and drain it. Then add the taco seasoning and water. Cook until the water thickens and the chicken is heated thoroughly.
While the chicken is cooking, drain and rinse the black beans.
Layer your tortilla chips on a large sheet pan. You only want one layer of chips so use a large enough sheet pan that chips don‚Äôt have to pile chips on top of each other.
Layer your beans on top of the chips. If using rice, layer it next. Then layer the chicken on top of the chips.
Top the nachos with the shredded cheese. If you‚Äôre adding onions or olives, layer them on next.
Bake for 5 minutes or until cheese is melted.
Remove from the oven and serve with desired toppings. If you‚Äôre adding tomatoes, lettuce, or avocado, add it after the nachos are done cooking.
For more Mexican flavor that‚Äôs easy, try making Crock Pot Chicken Enchiladas or Crockpot Chicken Tacos! You can also make all of these recipes for game day or other entertaining!
Easy Baked Nachos Recipe
Ingredients
- 1 lb
chicken(cut into small pieces) - 1 can
black beans(drained) - 1 packet
taco seasoning - 2 cups
shredded cheese tortilla chips- toppings - tomatoes, lettuce, onions, cilantro, avocado/guacamole, salsa, sour cream, etc.
Instructions
- Preheat the oven to 400¬∞F.
- Brown/cook the meat and drain. Add the taco seasoning and water. Cook until the water cooks off.
- Open, drain, and rinse black beans.
- Layer tortilla chips on a large sheet pan in a single layer.
- Top with black beans, chicken, and cheese.
- Place baking sheet in the oven and bake for 5 minutes or until cheese is melted.
- Remove from the oven and serve with desired toppings.

title: Germania, erosione della sabbia nelle isole del Mare del Nord a causa delle forti tempeste invernali
text:
MeteoWeb ¬ª METEO ¬ª IL METEO NEL MONDO Germania, erosione della sabbia nelle isole del Mare del Nord a causa delle forti tempeste invernali Nelle isole di Wangerooge, Norderney e Baltrum, le tempeste di vento e le conseguenti mareggiate hanno spazzato via la sabbia di Beatrice Raso 22 Mar 2024 | 21:32 Foto di David Hecker / Ansa MeteoWeb Le isole del Mare del Nord, in Germania, hanno sempre meno sabbia e ci√≤ √® dovuto alle forti tempeste che si sono verificate nel corso dell‚Äôinverno appena finito. Le tempeste di vento e le conseguenti mareggiate hanno spazzato via la sabbia, accentuando il fenomeno dell‚Äôerosione che era stato registrato anche negli anni precedenti.
A Wangerooge , le tempeste invernali hanno quasi completamente spazzato via la principale spiaggia balneare. ‚Äú √à un vero disastro‚Äù, ha dichiarato Rieka Beewen, rappresentante del sindaco dell‚Äôisola. Mancano quasi 80.000 metri cubi di sabbia e anche le isole di Norderney e Baltrum hanno registrato perdite significative di sabbia, cos√¨ come la localit√† pi√π famosa della Germania dal punto di vista turistico: l‚Äô isola di Sylt.
L‚Äôerosione delle spiagge crea problemi su due fronti. Il primo di natura ambientale , considerando che le dune a ridosso delle spiagge sono spesso sotto tutela e ospitano specie protette di piante e animali. Il secondo di natura turistica : le economie di molte delle isole del Mare del Nord, infatti, si basano principalmente sul turismo balneare. Il governo della Bassa Sassonia, il Land cui fanno parte le isole del Mare del Nord, ha promesso alle comunit√† isolane un aiuto finanziario per la ricostruzione delle infrastrutture turistiche. Iscrivendoti dichiari di aver preso visione delle condizioni generali del servizio . author: @KGNSnews
title: Experts give recommendations for allergy season in Laredo
text:
Experts give recommendations for allergy season in Laredo
LAREDO, Tex. (KGNS) - With many Laredo residents experiencing allergies this spring and summer, we consulted a medical professional about how to identify and treat these allergies.
For Laredoan Kelsey Salazar, she knows the allergies arrive once spring begins to bloom. She mentioned, ‚ÄúOne of the main things I do take into account is taking Benadryl or allergy medication.‚Äú
Health experts, including Family Nurse Practitioner Dr. Amanda Gallardo, indicate that tree and grass pollen are common triggers for those with allergies during the warmer months.
‚ÄúWe are coming up on allergy season, and we are in a transition right now. We are in spring, and it is important for the community and everyone to know allergy symptoms,‚Äú Gallardo said.
Some of the most common symptoms to watch out for include:
- Stuffy or runny nose
- Itching
- Watery eyes
- Sneezing
However, according to Gallardo, some symptoms are not as common. ‚ÄúEar pain is one because all the postnasal drip from the allergy is a reaction that creates congestion,‚Äù she added.
Fortunately, Salazar says her allergies haven‚Äôt been a big problem so far this season. She added, ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not to the extent that I need to go to the emergency room, thankfully.‚Äú
While some may experience allergies for a few hours or days, if you have severe allergies along with the symptoms previously listed, it is advised to call your doctor.
Gallardo added, ‚ÄúJust stay safe, as allergies can be very irritating.‚Äù Additionally, severe allergies may lead to a sinus infection due to congestion.

author: John and Nisha Whitehead
title: Who Owns America? Oligarchs Have Bought Up The American Dream ‚Äì OpEd
text:
Who owns America?
Is it the government? The politicians? The corporations? The foreign investors? The American people?
While the Deep State keeps the nation divided and distracted by a presidential election whose outcome is foregone (the police state‚Äôs stranglehold on power will ensure the continuation of endless wars and out-of-control spending, while disregarding the citizenry‚Äôs fundamental rights and the rule of law), America is literally being bought and sold right out from under us .
Consider the facts.
We‚Äôre losing more and more of our land every year to corporations and foreign interests. Foreign ownership of U.S. agricultural land has increased by 66% since 2010. In 2021, it was reported that foreign investors owned approximately 40 million acres of U.S. agricultural land , which is more than the entire state of Iowa. By 2022 that number had grown to 43.4 million acres . The rate at which U.S. farmland is being bought up by foreign interests grew by 2.2 million acres per year from 2015 to 2021. The number of U.S. farm acres owned by foreign entities grew more than 8% (3.4 million acres) in 2022.
We‚Äôre losing more and more of our businesses every year to foreign corporations and interests. Although China owns a small fraction of foreign-owned U.S. land at 380,000 acres (less than the state of Rhode Island), Chinese companies and investors are also buying up major food companies , commercial and residential real estate , and other businesses. As RetailWire explains, ‚ÄúCurrently, many brands started by early American pioneers now wave international flags. This revolution is a direct result of globalization .‚Äù The growing list of once-notable American brands that have been sold to foreign corporations includes: U.S. Steel (now Japanese-owned); General Electric (Chinese-owned); Budweiser (Belgium); Burger King (Canada); 7-Eleven (Japan); Jeep, Chrysler, and Dodge (Netherlands); and IBM (China).
We‚Äôre digging ourselves deeper and deeper into debt, both as a nation and as a populace. Basically, the U.S. government is funding its existence with a credit card, spending money it doesn‚Äôt have on programs it can‚Äôt afford. The bulk of that debt has been amassed over the past two decades , thanks in large part to the fiscal shenanigans of four presidents, 10 sessions of Congress and two wars. The national debt (the amount the federal government has borrowed over the years and must pay back) is more than $34 trillion and will grow another $19 trillion by 2033 . Foreign ownership makes up 29% of the U.S. debt held by the public . Of that amount, reports the Peter G. Peterson Foundation, ‚Äú52 percent was held by private foreign investors while foreign governments held the remaining 48 percent .‚Äù
The Fourth Estate has been taken over by media conglomerates that prioritize profit over principle. Independent news agencies, which were supposed to act as bulwarks against government propaganda, have been subsumed by a global corporate takeover of newspapers, television and radio. Consequently, a handful of corporations now control most of the media industry and, thus, the information dished out to the public. Likewise, with Facebook and Google having appointed themselves the arbiters of disinformation, we now find ourselves grappling with new levels of corporate censorship by entities with a history of colluding with the government to keep the citizenry mindless, muzzled and in the dark.
Most critically of all, however, the U.S. government, long ago sold to the highest bidders, has become little more than a shell company, a front for corporate interests. Nowhere is this state of affairs more evident than in the manufactured spectacle that is the presidential election. As for members of Congress, long before they‚Äôre elected, they are trained to dance to the tune of their wealthy benefactors, so much so that they spend two-thirds of their time in office raising money . As Reuters reports, ‚ÄúIt also means that lawmakers often spend more time listening to the concerns of the wealthy than anyone else.‚Äù
In the oligarchy that is the American police state, it clearly doesn‚Äôt matter who wins the White House, because they all work for the same boss: a Corporate State that has gone global.
So much for living the American dream.
‚ÄúWe the people‚Äù have become the new, permanent underclass in America.
We‚Äôre being forced to shell out money for endless wars that are bleeding us dry; money for surveillance systems to track our movements; money to further militarize our already militarized police; money to allow the government to raid our homes and bank accounts; money to fund schools where our kids learn nothing about freedom and everything about how to comply; and on and on.
This is no way of life.
It‚Äôs tempting to say that there‚Äôs little we can do about it, except that‚Äôs not quite accurate.
There are a few things we can do (demand transparency, reject cronyism and graft, insist on fair pricing and honest accounting methods, call a halt to incentive-driven government programs that prioritize profits over people), but it will require that ‚Äúwe the people‚Äù stop playing politics and stand united against the politicians and corporate interests who have turned our government and economy into a pay-to-play exercise in fascism.
Unfortunately, we‚Äôve become so invested in identity politics that label us based on our political leanings that we‚Äôve lost sight of the one label that unites us: we‚Äôre all Americans.
The powers-that-be want us to adopt an ‚Äúus versus them‚Äù mindset that keeps us powerless and divided. Yet as I make clear in my book Battlefield America: The War on the American People and in its fictional counterpart The Erik Blair Diaries , the only ‚Äúus versus them‚Äù that matters is ‚Äúwe the people‚Äù against the Deep State.
